Detailed User Stories (English Version)
Template Fetcher User Stories
Story 1: Basic Template Matching & Rendering
As a Gateway Service,
I want to invoke Template Fetcher with path, tags, language, and business variables,
So that I receive a fully rendered static HTML page using the most appropriate template.
Acceptance Criteria
Given a valid path, language, and variable set, when calling /api/template/fetch, the response returns 200 OK with text/html content type.
Given a path that maps to an active template, the returned HTML matches the template content with all variables replaced.
Given no matching template for the path, the system falls back to the global default template (if configured).
Technical Implementation Notes
Implement a TemplateFetcherController (Spring Boot REST) to expose the /api/template/fetch endpoint.
Use a TemplateMatcher service to query Template Manager’s /api/templates/match API with path/tags/lang parameters.
Use custom string replacement (no third-party template engines) to substitute {{variableName}} placeholders:
public String renderVariables(String templateHtml, Map<String, Object> variables) {
    String result = templateHtml;
    for (Map.Entry<String, Object> entry : variables.entrySet()) {
        String placeholder = "{{" + entry.getKey() + "}}";
        result = result.replace(placeholder, String.valueOf(entry.getValue()));
    }
    return result;
}
Story 2: Multi-Criteria Template Selection
As a Template Fetcher,
I want to match templates using multiple criteria (path, tags, language, library ID),
So that the most relevant template is selected even when multiple candidates exist.
Acceptance Criteria
Given multiple templates with the same path but different tags, the template with the highest tag match count is selected.
Given a template with exact path + language match, it is prioritized over templates with partial tag matches.
Given no exact path match, the system uses the template with the most matching tags + exact language.
Technical Implementation Notes
Implement a scoring algorithm in TemplateMatcher:
+10 points for exact path match
+5 points per matching tag
+3 points for exact language match
Select the template with the highest total score.
Use Spring Data JPA Specifications in Template Manager to build dynamic queries for multi-criteria filtering.
Story 3: Local Cache for Template Data
As a Template Fetcher,
I want to cache template metadata and raw HTML locally,
So that repeated requests avoid querying Template Manager and reduce latency.
Acceptance Criteria
Given a repeated request with the same path/tags/lang, the second request is served from cache (verified via cache hit logs).
Given a cached template, when the TTL expires, the next request fetches fresh data from Template Manager.
Given a cache size limit, the least recently used (LRU) templates are evicted when the limit is reached.
Technical Implementation Notes
Use Caffeine as the local cache provider (configured via Spring Cache):
spring.cache.type=caffeine
spring.cache.caffeine.spec=maximumSize=1000,expireAfterWrite=10m
Cache key format: template:{path}:{lang}:{tagsHash} (hash tags to keep key length manageable).
Annotate TemplateFetcherService methods with @Cacheable("templates") to enable caching.
Story 4: Cache Invalidation on Template Updates
As a Template Fetcher,
I want to invalidate cached templates when Template Manager updates/deletes a template,
So that stale template content is not served to users.
Acceptance Criteria
Given a cached template, when Template Manager sends an update event, the cache entry is removed.
Given a deleted template, all cache entries referencing that template are invalidated.
Given multiple Template Fetcher instances, all instances receive the invalidation event (distributed deployment).
Technical Implementation Notes
For single-instance deployments: Use Spring ApplicationEvent (publish TemplateUpdatedEvent from Template Manager, listen in Template Fetcher to evict cache).
For distributed deployments: Use RabbitMQ/Kafka to broadcast cache invalidation events across all instances.
Example event listener:
@EventListener
public void onTemplateUpdated(TemplateUpdatedEvent event) {
    String cacheKey = "template:" + event.getPath() + ":" + event.getLang();
    cacheManager.getCache("templates").evict(cacheKey);
}
Story 5: Multi-Language Support via Ref Data
As a Template Fetcher,
I want to integrate with Ref Data service to replace multi-language placeholders,
So that the rendered HTML displays localized content based on the user’s language preference.
Acceptance Criteria
Given a template with {{i18n.welcome.title}} and language zh-CN, the placeholder is replaced with the Chinese value from Ref Data.
Given a missing i18n key in the target language, the system falls back to the default language (e.g., en) value.
Given no value for a key in any language, the placeholder remains as {{i18n.key}} or shows [Missing Translation].
Technical Implementation Notes
Extract {{i18n.*}} placeholders using regex:
private Set<String> extractI18nKeys(String templateHtml) {
    Pattern pattern = Pattern.compile("\\{\\{i18n\\.(.*?)\\}\\}");
    Matcher matcher = pattern.matcher(templateHtml);
    Set<String> keys = new HashSet<>();
    while (matcher.find()) {
        keys.add(matcher.group(1));
    }
    return keys;
}
Call Ref Data API /api/i18n?lang={lang}&keys={comma-separated-keys} to fetch localized values in bulk.
Replace i18n placeholders before replacing business variables in the template.
Story 6: Fallback to Default Template
As a Template Fetcher,
I want to fall back to a pre-configured default template when no matching template is found,
So that the system returns a valid HTML page instead of an error response.
Acceptance Criteria
Given a path with no matching templates, the system returns the global default template.
Given a configured default template, it is used for all unmatched requests.
Given no default template configured, the system returns a 404 Not Found with a minimal error HTML.
Technical Implementation Notes
Define a @Value("${template.default.path}") property to specify the default template path.
In TemplateMatcher, if no templates are found, query the default template path.
If the default template also does not exist, return a minimal error HTML snippet.
Template Manager User Stories
Story 1: Create Template via Management UI
As a Template Administrator,
I want to create a new template via a web UI (with HTML editor, tag input, path, and language selection),
So that I can define new templates and persist them to the database.
Acceptance Criteria
Given the template creation page, when I enter a unique path, select a language, input HTML (with placeholders), and add tags, the template is saved to the database.
Given a duplicate path + lang combination, the system shows an error and prevents creation.
Given a valid submission, the new template appears in the list with active status.
Technical Implementation Notes
Build a Vue 3 + Element Plus frontend (or Thymeleaf for server-side rendering) for template management.
Implement a JPA entity Template with unique constraint on path + lang:
@Entity
@Table(name = "template", uniqueConstraints = @UniqueConstraint(columnNames = {"path", "lang"}))
public class Template {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;
    private String path;
    private String lang;
    @Column(columnDefinition = "TEXT")
    private String htmlContent;
    private String tags; // comma-separated
    private Integer version = 1;
    private Boolean isActive = true;
    private LocalDateTime createdAt = LocalDateTime.now();
    private LocalDateTime updatedAt = LocalDateTime.now();
    // getters/setters
}
Expose a POST /api/templates endpoint to handle creation requests.
Story 2: Edit/Delete Template via Management UI
As a Template Administrator,
I want to edit or delete existing templates via the web UI,
So that I can update template content or remove outdated templates.
Acceptance Criteria
Given an existing template, when I edit its HTML/tags and save, the template version increments by 1 (e.g., v1 → v2).
Given a deletion request, the template is marked as inactive (soft delete) or removed from the database (configurable).
Given an edited template, all cached entries for that template are invalidated.
Technical Implementation Notes
Expose PUT /api/templates/{id} and DELETE /api/templates/{id} endpoints.
Implement soft delete by setting isActive = false (preserves history) instead of hard deletion.
Publish TemplateUpdatedEvent/TemplateDeletedEvent after edit/delete to trigger cache invalidation in Template Fetcher.
Story 3: Template Metadata Management (Tags & Path)
As a Template Administrator,
I want to assign tags and a unique path to each template,
So that Template Fetcher can accurately locate templates based on routing and categorization.
Acceptance Criteria
Given a template, when I assign multiple tags (e.g., "homepage", "marketing"), the tags are stored as a comma-separated string.
Given a template path, it must be unique per language (no duplicate path + lang).
Given a tag search, the system returns all templates with matching tags.
Technical Implementation Notes
Store tags as a comma-separated string (or use a template_tag join table for better querying).
Use Spring Data JPA Specifications to build dynamic queries for filtering by tags/path/lang:
public List<Template> findByTagsContaining(String tag) {
    return templateRepository.findAll((root, query, cb) -> cb.like(root.get("tags"), "%" + tag + "%"));
}
Story 4: Template Version Control
As a Template Administrator,
I want to maintain version history for templates,
So that I can roll back to a previous version if a new template causes issues.
Acceptance Criteria
Given a template edit, the version number increments by 1.
Given a template, I can view all historical versions via the UI.
Given a previous version, I can restore it to the active state.
Technical Implementation Notes
Create a TemplateHistory entity to store all versions (copies of Template fields + version number).
On each edit, save the current state to TemplateHistory before updating the main Template record.
Expose GET /api/templates/{id}/history to retrieve version history.
Story 5: Template Query API for Template Fetcher
As a Template Fetcher Service,
I want to call Template Manager’s API with path, tags, and language parameters,
So that I can retrieve the best-matching template’s HTML content.
Acceptance Criteria
Given a request with path="/home", lang="en", tags="homepage", the API returns the highest-scoring matching template.
Given no matching templates, the API returns 404 Not Found (or the default template if configured).
Given a valid match, the API returns the template’s HTML, path, lang, and tags.
Technical Implementation Notes
Expose a GET /api/templates/match endpoint in Template Manager.
Implement the scoring algorithm (path match + tag match + lang match) in TemplateManagerService.
Example endpoint:
@GetMapping("/match")
public ResponseEntity<TemplateDTO> matchTemplate(
        @RequestParam String path,
        @RequestParam(required = false) String tags,
        @RequestParam(defaultValue = "en") String lang) {
    Template template = templateManagerService.findBestMatch(path, tags, lang);
    if (template == null) {
        return ResponseEntity.notFound().build();
    }
    return ResponseEntity.ok(new TemplateDTO(template));
}
Story 6: Template Preview Functionality
As a Template Administrator,
I want to preview a template with sample variables and language settings,
So that I can verify rendering before publishing.
Acceptance Criteria
Given a template and sample variables + language, the preview shows rendered HTML with variables and i18n text replaced.
Given a preview request, the system does not modify the template or cache.
Given invalid variables, the preview shows un-replaced placeholders.
Technical Implementation Notes
Expose a POST /api/templates/{id}/preview endpoint that accepts variables and lang parameters.
Reuse Template Fetcher’s rendering logic (variable + i18n replacement) to generate preview HTML.
Return the preview HTML as a response for the UI to display.
Story 7: Access Control for Template Management
As a Template Manager,
I want to restrict template creation/editing/deletion to authorized users,
So that templates are managed securely.
Acceptance Criteria
Given an unauthorized user, they cannot access the management UI or write API endpoints.
Given an admin user, they can perform all template operations.
Given a read-only user, they can view templates but cannot edit/delete.
Technical Implementation Notes
Use Spring Security for role-based access control:
@Configuration
public class SecurityConfig extends WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter {
    @Override
    protected void configure(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
        http.authorizeRequests()
            .antMatchers("/api/templates/**").hasRole("ADMIN")
            .antMatchers("/api/templates/match").permitAll()
            .and().formLogin();
    }
}
